      "id": "3d262e0e-8eb1-4cfd-bec5-864ef7465a06",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T06:17:10.334515+00:00",
      "type": "tool_result",
      "content": "```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"toolu_015a3Lx3LrnR5SmoVuW3JTej\",\n  \"name\": \"filesystem\",\n  \"content\": \"# AGENTS.md - AIFPL Source Directory\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThis directory contains the complete implementation of AIFPL (AI Functional Programming\\nLanguage) \\u2014 a pure functional language designed for use as an AI tool. This guide is\\nintended to help an AI navigate the design and assist with evolving the language.\\n\\n## Authoritative Language Reference\\n\\nThe authoritative description of AIFPL's language semantics, operators, and built-in\\nfunctions is the **AI tool description** (available to any AI in this system via the\\n`help` tool). Do not rely on README.md for language semantics \\u2014 it describes the\\nimplementation architecture only. When in doubt about language behaviour, use the\\nAIFPL tool directly to test.\\n\\n## Compiler Pipeline\\n\\nThe pipeline is orchestrated by `aifpl_compiler.py`, which chains the passes in this order:\\n\\n```\\nAIFPLLexer                  aifpl_lexer.py\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLParser                 aifpl_parser.py\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLSemanticAnalyzer       aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLModuleResolver         aifpl_module_resolver.py\\n    \\u2193  \\u2190 module ASTs are cached here (before optimization)\\nAIFPLDesugarer              aifpl_desugarer.py\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLConstantFolder         aifpl_constant_folder.py   (AST optimization pass)\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLIRBuilder              aifpl_ir_builder.py\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLCodeGen                aifpl_codegen.py\\n    \\u2193\\nAIFPLVM                     aifpl_vm.py\\n```\\n\\nKey design point: module resolution happens **before** desugaring and optimization,\\nso modules are compiled to resolved ASTs and cached. When the importing code runs,\\noptimizations are applied across module boundaries.\\n\\n## File-by-File Guide\\n\\n| File | Role | Size |\\n|------|------|------|\\n| `aifpl.py` | Public API (`AIFPL` class). Also contains `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` \\u2014 AIFPL source for variadic built-ins | Large |\\n| `aifpl_compiler.py` | Pipeline orchestrator \\u2014 read this first to understand the flow | Small |\\n| `aifpl_lexer.py` | Tokenizer | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_parser.py` | S-expression parser \\u2192 `AIFPLASTNode` tree | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py` | Scope analysis, arity checking, free variable detection | Large |\\n| `aifpl_module_resolver.py` | Resolves `import` forms, detects circular dependencies | Small |\\n| `aifpl_desugarer.py` | Expands all syntactic sugar: `let`, `let*`, `letrec`, `quote`, `match`, etc. \\u2192 canonical form | Very large |\\n| `aifpl_constant_folder.py` | AST-level constant folding optimization pass | Very large |\\n| `aifpl_optimization_pass.py` | Base class for AST optimization passes | Tiny |\\n| `aifpl_ir.py` | IR dataclasses (`AIFPLIRExpr` union type) \\u2014 the compilation plan | Small |\\n| `aifpl_ir_builder.py` | Lowers desugared AST \\u2192 IR. Resolves variable addressing, tail call detection | Large |\\n| `aifpl_codegen.py` | Lowers IR \\u2192 `CodeObject` bytecode | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_bytecode.py` | `Opcode` enum, `Instruction`, `CodeObject`, `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_bytecode_validator.py` | Validates bytecode correctness | Large |\\n| `aifpl_vm.py` | Stack-based bytecode VM. Executes `CodeObject`. Handles TCO, closures, trace | Very large |\\n| `aifpl_value.py` | All runtime value types (`AIFPLValue` hierarchy) | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_ast.py` | AST node types (`AIFPLASTNode` hierarchy) | Small |\\n| `aifpl_token.py` | Token type definitions | Tiny |\\n| `aifpl_builtin_registry.py` | Arity table for all builtins; generates bytecode stubs for fixed-arity builtins | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_error.py` | Exception hierarchy with structured error messages | Small |\\n| `aifpl_trace.py` | Trace watcher implementations | Small |\\n| `aifpl_pretty_printer.py` | AST pretty printer | Medium |\\n| `aifpl_dependency_analyzer.py` | Analyses binding group dependencies for `letrec` ordering | Small |\\n\\n## The Prelude\\n\\nMany built-in functions that appear variadic (e.g. `integer+`, `float*`, `string-concat`,\\n`list`, `list-concat`, `alist`, all typed comparison operators) are **implemented in AIFPL\\nitself** as lambdas in `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` inside `aifpl.py`. They fold over the\\nfixed binary-opcode versions internally.\\n\\nThere are three categories of builtin:\\n\\n- **Fixed-arity builtins** \\u2192 implemented as a bytecode stub in `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry`\\n  using a single opcode from `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` in `aifpl_bytecode.py`. The stub is\\n  a two-instruction `CodeObject` (`<opcode>` + `RETURN`) used when the builtin is passed\\n  as a first-class value.\\n- **Variadic builtins** \\u2192 implemented as AIFPL lambdas in `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` in `aifpl.py`,\\n  which call the fixed binary-arity opcode versions. These names are listed in\\n  `prelude_names` inside `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry.create_builtin_function_objects()` and are\\n  skipped by the registry so the prelude's compiled lambdas take effect instead.\\n- **Optional-argument builtins** \\u2192 a small set of builtins accept fewer arguments than\\n  their underlying opcode requires. The codegen (`aifpl_codegen.py`) synthesises the\\n  missing argument inline when emitting a direct call; the prelude supplies a wrapper\\n  lambda for first-class use. The affected builtins and their synthesised defaults are:\\n\\n  | Builtin | Optional arg | Synthesised default |\\n  |---------|-------------|---------------------|\\n  | `range` | `step` | `1` (integer constant) |\\n  | `string-slice` | `end` | `(string-length str)` \\u2014 re-evaluates the string arg |\\n  | `string->list` | `delimiter` | `\\\"\\\"` (empty string \\u2192 split into characters) |\\n  | `list-slice` | `end` | `(list-length lst)` \\u2014 re-evaluates the list arg |\\n  | `list->string` | `separator` | `\\\"\\\"` (empty string \\u2192 concatenate without separator) |\\n  | `alist-get` | `default` | `#f` |\\n\\n`AIFPLBuiltinRegistry.BUILTIN_OPCODE_ARITIES` is the arity table for **opcode-backed\\nbuiltins only** and is consumed by both the semantic analyser and the registry itself.\\nPure-AIFPL prelude functions (`list-map`, `list-filter`, `list-fold`, `list-zip`, `list-unzip`, `list-find`, `list-any?`,\\n`list-all?`, etc.) are **not** in this table and must **not** be added \\u2014 the registry asserts\\nthat every entry has a corresponding `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` entry, so adding a prelude-only\\nname will cause an assertion failure at startup. Prelude-only functions have their arity\\nenforced at runtime by the lambda itself, exactly like any user-defined function.\\n\\n## Variable Addressing and `LOAD_NAME`\\n\\nThe IR builder resolves all variable references to one of three addressing modes:\\n\\n- **`LOAD_VAR index`** \\u2014 lexically-addressed local variable in the current frame.\\n  Used for all user-defined bindings (`let`, `let*`, `letrec`, lambda parameters).\\n- **`LOAD_PARENT_VAR index depth`** \\u2014 lexically-addressed variable in an enclosing\\n  frame at `depth` levels up. Used for free variables captured from outer scopes\\n  (closures). Free variables are detected by the semantic analyser and captured via\\n  `MAKE_CLOSURE` at the call site.\\n- **`LOAD_NAME name_index`** \\u2014 name-table lookup, used **only for global builtins**\\n  that are referenced as first-class values (i.e. not called directly with the correct\\n  fixed arity). When the codegen sees a direct call to a known builtin at the right\\n  arity it emits the primitive opcode directly; `LOAD_NAME` is emitted when the\\n  builtin name appears as a variable reference (e.g. passed to `list-map` or `list-fold`).\\n  The name table is populated from `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry` by the VM at startup.\\n\\n## Design Decisions \\u2014 Clarifications\\n\\n- **No `cond` form**: Deliberate omission. `match` covers all multi-branch conditional\\n  use cases and is more expressive. Use nested `if` for simple two-branch conditions.\\n- **`integer-` vs `integer-neg`**: Both perform unary negation. `integer-` is the\\n  multi-arity subtraction operator that also handles the unary case (1 arg \\u2192 negate);\\n  `integer-neg` is the dedicated fixed-arity (1, 1) unary opcode. They are equivalent\\n  for single-argument calls. Prefer `integer-neg` when unary negation is the intent.\\n- **`symbol` type**: Symbols are produced only by `quote`. There is no `symbol->string`\\n  or `string->symbol` conversion by design \\u2014 symbols exist to support homoiconicity\\n  (code-as-data), not as a general-purpose key type. Use strings for alist keys.\\n- **Tail call optimization**: TCO is detected in `aifpl_ir_builder.py` (sets\\n  `is_tail_call` on `AIFPLIRCall`) and implemented via the `TAIL_CALL` opcode in the\\n  VM. It is correctly propagated through `let`/`let*`/`letrec` bodies, `if` branches,\\n  and `match` arms \\u2014 anywhere the body expression is in tail position.\\n- **Self-recursive tail calls**: In addition to the general `TAIL_CALL` mechanism,\\n  direct self-recursive calls (a function calling itself) are further optimised: the\\n  IR builder sets `is_tail_recursive` on the `AIFPLIRCall`, and the codegen emits a\\n  plain `JUMP 0` (back to the start of the function) instead of `TAIL_CALL`, avoiding\\n  even the overhead of a new frame setup.\\n\\n## Adding a New Built-in Function\\n\\n1. Add an opcode to the `Opcode` enum in `aifpl_bytecode.py`\\n2. Add the opcode \\u2192 arity mapping to `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` in `aifpl_bytecode.py`\\n3. Implement the opcode in `aifpl_vm.py`\\n4. Add the arity entry to `BUILTIN_OPCODE_ARITIES` in `aifpl_builtin_registry.py`\\n5. If variadic: add a prelude lambda to `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` in `aifpl.py` and add the\\n   name to `prelude_names` in `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry.create_builtin_function_objects()`\\n6. Update the tool description to document the new function\\n7. Add tests in `tests/aifpl/`\\n\\n## Adding a New Special Form\\n\\nSpecial forms (things that are not regular function calls) are handled in multiple places:\\n\\n1. **Desugarer** (`aifpl_desugarer.py`) \\u2014 if the form needs to be expanded into simpler\\n   forms before IR building\\n2. **IR builder** (`aifpl_ir_builder.py`) \\u2014 add a new `AIFPLIRXxx` dataclass in\\n   `aifpl_ir.py` and handle it in the IR builder\\n3. **Codegen** (`aifpl_codegen.py`) \\u2014 generate bytecode for the new IR node\\n4. **Semantic analyser** (`aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py`) \\u2014 if the form has scope or\\n   arity implications that need early checking\\n5. Update the tool description\\n\\n## Value Types\\n\\nAll runtime values are **immutable frozen dataclasses** inheriting from `AIFPLValue`\\nin `aifpl_value.py`. The full hierarchy:\\n\\n- `AIFPLInteger` \\u2014 Python `int`\\n- `AIFPLFloat` \\u2014 Python `float`\\n- `AIFPLComplex` \\u2014 Python `complex`\\n- `AIFPLString` \\u2014 Python `str`\\n- `AIFPLBoolean` \\u2014 Python `bool`\\n- `AIFPLSymbol` \\u2014 interned name (used for quoted symbols)\\n- `AIFPLList` \\u2014 backed by a Python `tuple` (proper lists only, no cons cells)\\n- `AIFPLAList` \\u2014 tuple of `(key, value)` pairs + hash-backed dict for O(1) lookup\\n- `AIFPLFunction` \\u2014 compiled lambda or builtin stub; carries `CodeObject`, captured\\n  values, and variadic flag\\n\\n## Key Design Decisions\\n\\n- **Proper lists only**: `AIFPLList` is backed by a Python tuple. There are no cons\\n  cells or improper lists. `cons` requires the second argument to be a list.\\n- **Strict typing**: No implicit coercion between numeric types. All operators are\\n  type-specific (e.g. `integer+`, `float*`).\\n- **Tail call optimization**: Detected in `aifpl_ir_builder.py` (sets `is_tail_call`\\n  on `AIFPLIRCall`), implemented in `aifpl_vm.py` via `TAIL_CALL` opcode.\\n- **Closures**: Free variables are detected in `aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py` and\\n  captured via `MAKE_CLOSURE` opcode in the VM.\\n- **Homoiconicity**: Quoted expressions produce `AIFPLList`/`AIFPLSymbol` values\\n  identical in structure to the AST they represent.\\n\\n## Tests\\n\\nTests mirror the source structure under `tests/aifpl/`. When making changes, run the\\ntest suite to verify correctness. The `tools/` directory contains additional utilities:\\n- `aifpl_disassembler/` \\u2014 inspect generated bytecode\\n- `aifpl_bytecode_analyzer/` \\u2014 analyse bytecode patterns\\n- `aifpl_checker/` \\u2014 static analysis\\n- `aifpl_benchmark/` \\u2014 performance testing\\n\",\n  \"error\": null\n}\n```\n`content` is:\n```markdown\n# AGENTS.md - AIFPL Source Directory\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis directory contains the complete implementation of AIFPL (AI Functional Programming\nLanguage) \u2014 a pure functional language designed for use as an AI tool. This guide is\nintended to help an AI navigate the design and assist with evolving the language.\n\n## Authoritative Language Reference\n\nThe authoritative description of AIFPL's language semantics, operators, and built-in\nfunctions is the **AI tool description** (available to any AI in this system via the\n`help` tool). Do not rely on README.md for language semantics \u2014 it describes the\nimplementation architecture only. When in doubt about language behaviour, use the\nAIFPL tool directly to test.\n\n## Compiler Pipeline\n\nThe pipeline is orchestrated by `aifpl_compiler.py`, which chains the passes in this order:\n\n```\nAIFPLLexer                  aifpl_lexer.py\n    \u2193\nAIFPLParser                 aifpl_parser.py\n    \u2193\nAIFPLSemanticAnalyzer       aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py\n    \u2193\nAIFPLModuleResolver         aifpl_module_resolver.py\n    \u2193  \u2190 module ASTs are cached here (before optimization)\nAIFPLDesugarer              aifpl_desugarer.py\n    \u2193\nAIFPLConstantFolder         aifpl_constant_folder.py   (AST optimization pass)\n    \u2193\nAIFPLIRBuilder              aifpl_ir_builder.py\n    \u2193\nAIFPLCodeGen                aifpl_codegen.py\n    \u2193\nAIFPLVM                     aifpl_vm.py\n```\n\nKey design point: module resolution happens **before** desugaring and optimization,\nso modules are compiled to resolved ASTs and cached. When the importing code runs,\noptimizations are applied across module boundaries.\n\n## File-by-File Guide\n\n| File | Role | Size |\n|------|------|------|\n| `aifpl.py` | Public API (`AIFPL` class). Also contains `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` \u2014 AIFPL source for variadic built-ins | Large |\n| `aifpl_compiler.py` | Pipeline orchestrator \u2014 read this first to understand the flow | Small |\n| `aifpl_lexer.py` | Tokenizer | Medium |\n| `aifpl_parser.py` | S-expression parser \u2192 `AIFPLASTNode` tree | Medium |\n| `aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py` | Scope analysis, arity checking, free variable detection | Large |\n| `aifpl_module_resolver.py` | Resolves `import` forms, detects circular dependencies | Small |\n| `aifpl_desugarer.py` | Expands all syntactic sugar: `let`, `let*`, `letrec`, `quote`, `match`, etc. \u2192 canonical form | Very large |\n| `aifpl_constant_folder.py` | AST-level constant folding optimization pass | Very large |\n| `aifpl_optimization_pass.py` | Base class for AST optimization passes | Tiny |\n| `aifpl_ir.py` | IR dataclasses (`AIFPLIRExpr` union type) \u2014 the compilation plan | Small |\n| `aifpl_ir_builder.py` | Lowers desugared AST \u2192 IR. Resolves variable addressing, tail call detection | Large |\n| `aifpl_codegen.py` | Lowers IR \u2192 `CodeObject` bytecode | Medium |\n| `aifpl_bytecode.py` | `Opcode` enum, `Instruction`, `CodeObject`, `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` | Medium |\n| `aifpl_bytecode_validator.py` | Validates bytecode correctness | Large |\n| `aifpl_vm.py` | Stack-based bytecode VM. Executes `CodeObject`. Handles TCO, closures, trace | Very large |\n| `aifpl_value.py` | All runtime value types (`AIFPLValue` hierarchy) | Medium |\n| `aifpl_ast.py` | AST node types (`AIFPLASTNode` hierarchy) | Small |\n| `aifpl_token.py` | Token type definitions | Tiny |\n| `aifpl_builtin_registry.py` | Arity table for all builtins; generates bytecode stubs for fixed-arity builtins | Medium |\n| `aifpl_error.py` | Exception hierarchy with structured error messages | Small |\n| `aifpl_trace.py` | Trace watcher implementations | Small |\n| `aifpl_pretty_printer.py` | AST pretty printer | Medium |\n| `aifpl_dependency_analyzer.py` | Analyses binding group dependencies for `letrec` ordering | Small |\n\n## The Prelude\n\nMany built-in functions that appear variadic (e.g. `integer+`, `float*`, `string-concat`,\n`list`, `list-concat`, `alist`, all typed comparison operators) are **implemented in AIFPL\nitself** as lambdas in `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` inside `aifpl.py`. They fold over the\nfixed binary-opcode versions internally.\n\nThere are three categories of builtin:\n\n- **Fixed-arity builtins** \u2192 implemented as a bytecode stub in `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry`\n  using a single opcode from `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` in `aifpl_bytecode.py`. The stub is\n  a two-instruction `CodeObject` (`<opcode>` + `RETURN`) used when the builtin is passed\n  as a first-class value.\n- **Variadic builtins** \u2192 implemented as AIFPL lambdas in `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` in `aifpl.py`,\n  which call the fixed binary-arity opcode versions. These names are listed in\n  `prelude_names` inside `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry.create_builtin_function_objects()` and are\n  skipped by the registry so the prelude's compiled lambdas take effect instead.\n- **Optional-argument builtins** \u2192 a small set of builtins accept fewer arguments than\n  their underlying opcode requires. The codegen (`aifpl_codegen.py`) synthesises the\n  missing argument inline when emitting a direct call; the prelude supplies a wrapper\n  lambda for first-class use. The affected builtins and their synthesised defaults are:\n\n  | Builtin | Optional arg | Synthesised default |\n  |---------|-------------|---------------------|\n  | `range` | `step` | `1` (integer constant) |\n  | `string-slice` | `end` | `(string-length str)` \u2014 re-evaluates the string arg |\n  | `string->list` | `delimiter` | `\"\"` (empty string \u2192 split into characters) |\n  | `list-slice` | `end` | `(list-length lst)` \u2014 re-evaluates the list arg |\n  | `list->string` | `separator` | `\"\"` (empty string \u2192 concatenate without separator) |\n  | `alist-get` | `default` | `#f` |\n\n`AIFPLBuiltinRegistry.BUILTIN_OPCODE_ARITIES` is the arity table for **opcode-backed\nbuiltins only** and is consumed by both the semantic analyser and the registry itself.\nPure-AIFPL prelude functions (`list-map`, `list-filter`, `list-fold`, `list-zip`, `list-unzip`, `list-find`, `list-any?`,\n`list-all?`, etc.) are **not** in this table and must **not** be added \u2014 the registry asserts\nthat every entry has a corresponding `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` entry, so adding a prelude-only\nname will cause an assertion failure at startup. Prelude-only functions have their arity\nenforced at runtime by the lambda itself, exactly like any user-defined function.\n\n## Variable Addressing and `LOAD_NAME`\n\nThe IR builder resolves all variable references to one of three addressing modes:\n\n- **`LOAD_VAR index`** \u2014 lexically-addressed local variable in the current frame.\n  Used for all user-defined bindings (`let`, `let*`, `letrec`, lambda parameters).\n- **`LOAD_PARENT_VAR index depth`** \u2014 lexically-addressed variable in an enclosing\n  frame at `depth` levels up. Used for free variables captured from outer scopes\n  (closures). Free variables are detected by the semantic analyser and captured via\n  `MAKE_CLOSURE` at the call site.\n- **`LOAD_NAME name_index`** \u2014 name-table lookup, used **only for global builtins**\n  that are referenced as first-class values (i.e. not called directly with the correct\n  fixed arity). When the codegen sees a direct call to a known builtin at the right\n  arity it emits the primitive opcode directly; `LOAD_NAME` is emitted when the\n  builtin name appears as a variable reference (e.g. passed to `list-map` or `list-fold`).\n  The name table is populated from `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry` by the VM at startup.\n\n## Design Decisions \u2014 Clarifications\n\n- **No `cond` form**: Deliberate omission. `match` covers all multi-branch conditional\n  use cases and is more expressive. Use nested `if` for simple two-branch conditions.\n- **`integer-` vs `integer-neg`**: Both perform unary negation. `integer-` is the\n  multi-arity subtraction operator that also handles the unary case (1 arg \u2192 negate);\n  `integer-neg` is the dedicated fixed-arity (1, 1) unary opcode. They are equivalent\n  for single-argument calls. Prefer `integer-neg` when unary negation is the intent.\n- **`symbol` type**: Symbols are produced only by `quote`. There is no `symbol->string`\n  or `string->symbol` conversion by design \u2014 symbols exist to support homoiconicity\n  (code-as-data), not as a general-purpose key type. Use strings for alist keys.\n- **Tail call optimization**: TCO is detected in `aifpl_ir_builder.py` (sets\n  `is_tail_call` on `AIFPLIRCall`) and implemented via the `TAIL_CALL` opcode in the\n  VM. It is correctly propagated through `let`/`let*`/`letrec` bodies, `if` branches,\n  and `match` arms \u2014 anywhere the body expression is in tail position.\n- **Self-recursive tail calls**: In addition to the general `TAIL_CALL` mechanism,\n  direct self-recursive calls (a function calling itself) are further optimised: the\n  IR builder sets `is_tail_recursive` on the `AIFPLIRCall`, and the codegen emits a\n  plain `JUMP 0` (back to the start of the function) instead of `TAIL_CALL`, avoiding\n  even the overhead of a new frame setup.\n\n## Adding a New Built-in Function\n\n1. Add an opcode to the `Opcode` enum in `aifpl_bytecode.py`\n2. Add the opcode \u2192 arity mapping to `BUILTIN_OPCODE_MAP` in `aifpl_bytecode.py`\n3. Implement the opcode in `aifpl_vm.py`\n4. Add the arity entry to `BUILTIN_OPCODE_ARITIES` in `aifpl_builtin_registry.py`\n5. If variadic: add a prelude lambda to `_PRELUDE_SOURCE` in `aifpl.py` and add the\n   name to `prelude_names` in `AIFPLBuiltinRegistry.create_builtin_function_objects()`\n6. Update the tool description to document the new function\n7. Add tests in `tests/aifpl/`\n\n## Adding a New Special Form\n\nSpecial forms (things that are not regular function calls) are handled in multiple places:\n\n1. **Desugarer** (`aifpl_desugarer.py`) \u2014 if the form needs to be expanded into simpler\n   forms before IR building\n2. **IR builder** (`aifpl_ir_builder.py`) \u2014 add a new `AIFPLIRXxx` dataclass in\n   `aifpl_ir.py` and handle it in the IR builder\n3. **Codegen** (`aifpl_codegen.py`) \u2014 generate bytecode for the new IR node\n4. **Semantic analyser** (`aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py`) \u2014 if the form has scope or\n   arity implications that need early checking\n5. Update the tool description\n\n## Value Types\n\nAll runtime values are **immutable frozen dataclasses** inheriting from `AIFPLValue`\nin `aifpl_value.py`. The full hierarchy:\n\n- `AIFPLInteger` \u2014 Python `int`\n- `AIFPLFloat` \u2014 Python `float`\n- `AIFPLComplex` \u2014 Python `complex`\n- `AIFPLString` \u2014 Python `str`\n- `AIFPLBoolean` \u2014 Python `bool`\n- `AIFPLSymbol` \u2014 interned name (used for quoted symbols)\n- `AIFPLList` \u2014 backed by a Python `tuple` (proper lists only, no cons cells)\n- `AIFPLAList` \u2014 tuple of `(key, value)` pairs + hash-backed dict for O(1) lookup\n- `AIFPLFunction` \u2014 compiled lambda or builtin stub; carries `CodeObject`, captured\n  values, and variadic flag\n\n## Key Design Decisions\n\n- **Proper lists only**: `AIFPLList` is backed by a Python tuple. There are no cons\n  cells or improper lists. `cons` requires the second argument to be a list.\n- **Strict typing**: No implicit coercion between numeric types. All operators are\n  type-specific (e.g. `integer+`, `float*`).\n- **Tail call optimization**: Detected in `aifpl_ir_builder.py` (sets `is_tail_call`\n  on `AIFPLIRCall`), implemented in `aifpl_vm.py` via `TAIL_CALL` opcode.\n- **Closures**: Free variables are detected in `aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py` and\n  captured via `MAKE_CLOSURE` opcode in the VM.\n- **Homoiconicity**: Quoted expressions produce `AIFPLList`/`AIFPLSymbol` values\n  identical in structure to the AST they represent.\n\n## Tests\n\nTests mirror the source structure under `tests/aifpl/`. When making changes, run the\ntest suite to verify correctness. The `tools/` directory contains additional utilities:\n- `aifpl_disassembler/` \u2014 inspect generated bytecode\n- `aifpl_bytecode_analyzer/` \u2014 analyse bytecode patterns\n- `aifpl_checker/` \u2014 static analysis\n- `aifpl_benchmark/` \u2014 performance testing\n\n```",
