    {
      "id": "899ee09e-b0c6-42aa-b23a-ba606a9f39c7",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T06:17:11.714971+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "I now have a solid picture of the codebase and the AIFPL alist design. Let me share what I know so we can have a focused discussion.\n\n---\n\nGreat \u2014 I'm well oriented. Here's a summary of the current **alist design** in AIFPL as I understand it, so we have a common baseline for the discussion:\n\n---\n\n## Current Alist Design\n\n### Runtime Representation\n`AIFPLAList` is a **frozen dataclass** backed by:\n- A tuple of `(key, value)` pairs (preserving **insertion order**)\n- A hash-backed dict for **O(1) lookup**\n\nThis gives it map semantics with deterministic ordering \u2014 a good fit for an AI tool where output predictability matters.\n\n### Construction\n```aifpl\n(alist (list \"name\" \"Alice\") (list \"age\" 30))\n```\nThe `alist` constructor is a **variadic prelude lambda** that folds over `(list key value)` pairs. Keys are strings.\n\n### Operations\n| Operation | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `alist-get` | Lookup with optional default (defaults to `#f`) |\n| `alist-set` | Return new alist with key set (immutable update) |\n| `alist-remove` | Return new alist without key |\n| `alist-has?` | Predicate |\n| `alist-keys` | Returns list of keys |\n| `alist-values` | Returns list of values |\n| `alist-length` | Number of entries |\n| `alist-merge` | Merge two alists (second wins on conflict) |\n| `alist=?` / `alist!=?` | Equality comparison |\n| `alist?` | Type predicate |\n\n### Notable Design Points\n- **String-only keys** (by convention/design \u2014 symbols are deliberately not the key type)\n- **No `alist-map` / `alist-filter`** (noted as pending improvement #19)\n- Nested alists are supported naturally\n- Works with `match` via the `(alist? a)` pattern\n- `alist-get` has an **optional default argument** synthesised by codegen\n\n---\n\nWhat aspect of the alist design would you like to discuss? For example:\n- The missing `alist-map`/`alist-filter` operations (#19)?\n- Key type restrictions (string-only vs. allowing other types)?\n- The construction syntax (`(list key value)` pairs)?\n- Performance characteristics?\n- Something else entirely?",
