    {
      "id": "e2db2a30-856f-407a-927e-ff984308118f",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T06:36:29.986938+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Yes, that's a really important clarification. Let me think through what you actually have and what you actually need.\n\n---\n\n## What You Have vs. What You're Calling It\n\nCurrent \"alist\" is already a **dict** in every meaningful sense:\n- O(1) lookup by string key\n- No duplicate keys (set semantics on keys)\n- Insertion-order preserved\n- Immutable update returns new value\n\nA true alist would allow duplicate keys, have O(n) lookup, and `alist-get` would return the first match. You have none of that. The name is a misnomer.\n\n---\n\n## The Record / Struct Use Case\n\nFor structured records, the interesting question is: **what does the access pattern look like in practice?**\n\nA record typically has:\n- A **fixed, known set of fields** at write time\n- **Field access by name** as the dominant operation\n- Rarely iterated as key/value pairs\n- Possibly **nested** records\n\nCompare to a dynamic dict which has:\n- **Unknown keys** at write time\n- Mixed access patterns\n- Often iterated\n\nThese are genuinely different use cases, and conflating them into one type may be part of why the current design feels slightly off.\n\n---\n\n## The Performance Angle\n\nFor records specifically, if fields are known at compile time you can do much better than a hash lookup:\n\n- **Slot-based access** \u2014 fields are positional, access is O(1) array index, no hashing at all\n- **Shape/schema sharing** \u2014 many record instances share the same field layout, so the schema is stored once\n- **Uniqueness optimisation** becomes trivial \u2014 a record with one reference can update a slot in place\n\nThis is essentially how JavaScript V8's \"hidden classes\" work, and how Python `__slots__` works. The key enabler is that the **field names are statically known**.\n\n---\n\n## So What Are You Actually Missing?\n\nI think there are potentially **two distinct types** hiding in your current design:\n\n### Type 1: `dict` \u2014 dynamic, string-keyed map\nRename/rebrand what you have. Unknown keys at write time, iterable, merge-able. Good for flexible data. Keep the current implementation.\n\n### Type 2: `record` \u2014 fixed-schema structured value\nNew type. Fields declared at construction, accessed by name, schema potentially reused across instances. Much faster field access, more natural for object-like use.\n\nSomething like:\n```aifpl\n(record (\"name\" \"Alice\") (\"age\" 30) (\"role\" \"admin\"))\n(record-get my-record \"name\")\n(record-set my-record \"age\" 31)  ; returns new record, same schema\n```\n\nThe crucial difference from dict: `record-set` cannot add new keys \u2014 the schema is fixed at construction. That constraint is what enables the slot-based optimisation.\n\n---\n\n## The Practical Question\n\nBefore going further \u2014 which use case is actually driving this? Are you finding yourself wanting to model **structured objects with known fields** (\u2192 record), or **flexible runtime mappings** (\u2192 dict), or both? Because the right answer to \"what should replace/complement alist\" depends heavily on which problem you're actually trying to solve.",
