    {
      "id": "05bc0aa7-4987-426c-a928-5782f463d78a",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T06:37:57.338277+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Right, so the question becomes: do you want **two separate types** or **one unified type** that handles both well?\n\n---\n\n## The Case for Two Separate Types\n\nClean separation of concerns:\n- `dict` \u2014 dynamic, unknown keys, iterable, mergeable, no schema\n- `record` \u2014 fixed schema, slot-based access, schema shared across instances\n\nThe user picks the right tool. The compiler/VM can optimise each independently. The type predicates (`dict?`, `record?`) let `match` dispatch cleanly.\n\nThe downside: **the boundary is often blurry in practice**. You start with a record, then need to add a field dynamically, and now you're converting between types. Or you're building a record incrementally and it feels like a dict until it's \"done.\"\n\n---\n\n## The Case for One Unified Type\n\nOne type with **two operational modes** \u2014 the runtime promotes from dict-mode to record-mode when it detects a stable schema. The user never thinks about it.\n\nThe downside: **the optimisation becomes implicit and unpredictable**. The user can't reason about when they're getting slot-based access vs. hash lookup. And the \"stable schema\" detection is genuinely hard to get right.\n\n---\n\n## The More Interesting Question\n\nI think the real tension isn't dict vs. record \u2014 it's about **when the schema is known**:\n\n| | Schema known? | Key addition after construction? |\n|---|---|---|\n| Current alist/dict | No | Yes |\n| Record | Yes, at construction | No |\n| \"Builder\" pattern | No during build, yes after | No after seal |\n\nThat third row is interesting. Many record-like use cases are actually **two-phase**:\n1. Build phase \u2014 accumulate fields, schema unknown\n2. Use phase \u2014 schema fixed, read-heavy, optimise access\n\nIf you had a way to **seal** a dict into a record, you get the best of both:\n```aifpl\n(let* ((d (dict (\"name\" \"Alice\") (\"age\" 30)))\n       (r (record-seal d)))\n  (record-get r \"name\"))\n```\n\nAfter `record-seal`, the schema is fixed, slot layout is computed once, and all subsequent access is O(1) array index. The sealing step is also a natural point for the **uniqueness optimisation** \u2014 if `d` has one reference at seal time, no copy is needed.\n\n---\n\n## My Practical Suggestion\n\nGiven that you'll have both use cases, I'd lean toward:\n\n1. **Rename current alist \u2192 dict** \u2014 it's already the right implementation, just misnamed\n2. **Add record as a distinct type** \u2014 fixed schema, slot-based, constructed either directly or by sealing a dict\n3. **`record-seal`** as the bridge between the two phases\n\nThis keeps the types honest, gives the compiler clear optimisation targets, and maps naturally onto the uniqueness/mutation work you're planning. The user always knows which mode they're in.\n\nDoes the sealing concept feel right, or does it add too much friction to the common case?",
