    {
      "id": "4aeb4e9b-0162-4afc-81da-a3f0293d44cf",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T06:40:17.626681+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Exactly right, and this is a strong argument for keeping them as two distinct types rather than one unified type.\n\n---\n\n## The Operational Signatures Tell the Story\n\n**List** \u2014 ordered sequence, mapping preserves order and structure:\n```aifpl\n(list-map f (list 1 2 3)) \u2192 (list 2 4 6)\n```\n\n**Dict** \u2014 unordered key/value pairs, mapping over values makes sense:\n```aifpl\n(dict-map f my-dict)      \u2192 new dict, same keys, f applied to each value\n(dict-filter pred my-dict) \u2192 new dict, entries where pred of (key value) is true\n```\n\n**Record** \u2014 fixed schema, fields have *meaning*, mapping over them makes no sense semantically. What would it even mean to double every field of a `(\"name\" \"Alice\") (\"age\" 30)` record? The fields are heterogeneous by design.\n\n---\n\n## The Type Hierarchy This Implies\n\nEach type has a natural and coherent operation set:\n\n| Operation | list | dict | record |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `*-map` | \u2713 | \u2713 (over values) | \u2717 |\n| `*-filter` | \u2713 | \u2713 (over entries) | \u2717 |\n| `*-fold` | \u2713 | \u2713 | \u2717 |\n| `*-get` | by index | by key | by field name |\n| `*-set` | \u2717 (immutable) | new dict, any key | new record, existing fields only |\n| `*-keys` | \u2717 | \u2713 | maybe, but static |\n| `*-merge` | `list-concat` | \u2713 | \u2717 |\n| `*-length` | \u2713 | \u2713 | \u2717 (schema is fixed, not a runtime property) |\n\nThe record column being mostly \u2717 for higher-order operations is actually a **feature** \u2014 it tells you the type is doing the right job. Records aren't collections to be iterated, they're structured values to be destructured.\n\n---\n\n## The Naming Convention Follows Naturally\n\nWith the prefix convention you're already moving toward:\n- `list-map`, `list-filter`, `list-fold` \u2014 sequence operations\n- `dict-map`, `dict-filter`, `dict-fold` \u2014 key/value operations  \n- `record-get`, `record-set`, `record-has?` \u2014 field access only, no higher-order ops\n\nThis is clean, consistent, and self-documenting. An AI using the language immediately knows from the prefix what kind of value it's working with, and what operations are available.\n\n---\n\n## One Subtlety Worth Noting\n\n`dict-map` has an ambiguity: does `f` receive just the value, or the key-value pair? Both are useful:\n\n```aifpl\n(dict-map-values f my-dict)   ; f receives value, key preserved\n(dict-map f my-dict)          ; f receives (key value), returns new value\n```\n\nWorth deciding upfront, since it affects how natural dict transformations feel in practice. Python's dict went with values-only for `map`-like operations; Clojure's `map` over a map gives you key-value pairs. The two-argument form is more powerful but slightly more verbose for the common case.",
