      "id": "0c21d4d8-cfdc-4ca6-bac5-e200852f5ec7",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T10:48:18.161300+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Let me think through this carefully, because the record type is the most novel addition and getting the API right matters.\n\n---\n\n## Core Semantics\n\nA record is:\n- **Fixed schema** \u2014 fields defined at construction, cannot be added or removed\n- **Heterogeneous** \u2014 fields have different types by design\n- **Named fields** \u2014 accessed by string name, not position\n- **Immutable to the user** \u2014 `record-set` returns a new record with the same schema\n- **No higher-order ops** \u2014 not a collection, not iterable in the `map`/`filter` sense\n\n---\n\n## Construction\n\nThe straightforward approach mirrors dict construction:\n```aifpl\n(record (\"name\" \"Alice\") (\"age\" 30) (\"role\" \"admin\"))\n```\n\nBut records have a schema \u2014 and if schema sharing is the performance goal, you want the schema to be **reusable** across instances. This suggests a two-step construction:\n\n```aifpl\n(let ((person-schema (record-schema \"name\" \"age\" \"role\")))\n  (record-make person-schema \"Alice\" 30 \"admin\"))\n```\n\nThe schema is created once, instances are cheap. Field access uses slot index, not hash lookup.\n\nHowever this may be **too much friction** for the common case. An alternative is to infer the schema implicitly:\n\n```aifpl\n(record (\"name\" \"Alice\") (\"age\" 30) (\"role\" \"admin\"))\n```\n\nThe runtime interns the schema based on the ordered set of field names \u2014 two records with the same fields in the same order share a schema automatically. The user never thinks about it.\n\nThe implicit approach is cleaner for an AI tool language. The explicit schema approach is better if you want schema-as-a-value (for validation, introspection, etc.).\n\n---\n\n## Field Access and Update\n\n```aifpl\n(record-get my-record \"name\")           ; \u2192 \"Alice\"\n(record-get my-record \"missing\")        ; \u2192 error? or #f?\n(record-get my-record \"missing\" \"default\")  ; \u2192 \"default\" (optional default like dict-get)\n\n(record-set my-record \"age\" 31)         ; \u2192 new record, same schema\n(record-set my-record \"new-field\" \"x\")  ; \u2192 error, schema violation\n```\n\nThe `record-set` schema violation is the key behavioural difference from dict. It's a runtime error if you try to add a field that wasn't in the original schema.\n\n---\n\n## Predicates and Introspection\n\n```aifpl\n(record? x)                    ; type predicate\n(record-has? my-record \"name\") ; field exists in schema \u2014 always static, but useful\n(record-schema? s)             ; is s a schema value\n```\n\n`record-has?` is interesting \u2014 for a fixed schema it's always deterministic, so the compiler could constant-fold it away entirely in most cases. Useful for defensive code.\n\n---\n\n## Schema Introspection\n\nShould you be able to inspect a record's schema at runtime?\n\n```aifpl\n(record-fields my-record)   ; \u2192 (list \"name\" \"age\" \"role\") \u2014 field names in order\n```\n\nThis is the one concession to \"collection-like\" behaviour that probably makes sense \u2014 not for iteration, but for generic code that needs to know what it's working with. Useful in `match` arms, serialisation, debugging.\n\nNotably absent: `record-values` and `record-length`. Those push toward treating it as a collection, which is the wrong direction.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern Matching\n\nThis is where record really shines:\n\n```aifpl\n(match my-record\n  ((record? r) (record-get r \"name\"))\n  (_ \"not a record\"))\n```\n\nBut you could go further with **field destructuring** in match:\n\n```aifpl\n(match my-record\n  ((\"name\" n \"age\" a) (string-concat n \" is \" (integer->string a)))\n  (_ \"unknown\"))\n```\n\nThis is powerful but adds complexity to the pattern matcher. Worth considering as a future addition rather than day one.\n\n---\n\n## What's Deliberately Absent\n\n- `record-map`, `record-filter`, `record-fold` \u2014 not a collection\n- `record-merge` \u2014 schemas would conflict, use dict for that\n- `record-length` \u2014 schema is fixed, this isn't a meaningful runtime property\n- `record-keys`, `record-values` \u2014 pushes toward collection semantics\n- Any way to convert a record to a dict implicitly \u2014 should be explicit if needed\n\n---\n\n## The Bridge to Dict\n\nOne explicit conversion in each direction is probably warranted:\n\n```aifpl\n(record->dict my-record)   ; \u2192 dict with same key/value pairs, now dynamic\n(dict->record my-dict)     ; \u2192 record with schema inferred from dict's keys\n```\n\n`dict->record` is essentially the `record-seal` idea from earlier \u2014 the natural end of the build phase.\n\n---\n\n## Summary API\n\n| Operation | Notes |\n|---|---|\n| `(record (k v) ...)` | Construction, schema interned implicitly |\n| `(record-get r k)` | Field access, optional default |\n| `(record-set r k v)` | Returns new record, error if k not in schema |\n| `(record-has? r k)` | Schema membership, compiler can constant-fold |\n| `(record-fields r)` | Returns list of field names |\n| `(record? x)` | Type predicate |\n| `(record->dict r)` | Explicit conversion to dict |\n| `(dict->record d)` | Explicit conversion from dict, seals schema |\n| `(record=? r1 r2)` | Equality |\n| `(record!=? r1 r2)` | Inequality |\n\n---\n\nDoes this feel right? The main open questions I see are:\n\n1. **Implicit vs. explicit schema** \u2014 intern automatically or expose `record-schema` as a value?\n2. **`record-get` on missing field** \u2014 error or default?\n3. **Match destructuring** \u2014 day one or future addition?",
