    {
      "id": "faf0c827-71d6-4ff9-afe8-0f8a1e0a4cca",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T10:53:03.637943+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Good, I can see the full picture now. Let me think through the implementation carefully.\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight from the Current Code\n\n`AIFPLAList` already shows the pattern clearly:\n- `pairs` \u2014 the ordered data (a frozen tuple)\n- `_lookup` \u2014 the auxiliary hash index, built in `__post_init__`, stored via `object.__setattr__` to bypass the frozen constraint\n\nA record would follow **exactly the same pattern**, with one crucial addition: a **shared schema object**.\n\n---\n\n## The Schema Object\n\nThis is the heart of the implementation. A schema is just an ordered mapping of field name \u2192 slot index:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass AIFPLRecordSchema:\n    fields: Tuple[str, ...]                    # ordered field names\n    index: dict[str, int]                      # name \u2192 slot index, for O(1) access\n```\n\nSchemas are **interned** \u2014 a global `dict[Tuple[str, ...], AIFPLRecordSchema]` keyed by the ordered tuple of field names. Two records with the same fields in the same order share one schema object. The interning is a Python-level detail, invisible to the user.\n\n---\n\n## The Record Value\n\n```python\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass AIFPLRecord(AIFPLValue):\n    schema: AIFPLRecordSchema\n    slots: Tuple[AIFPLValue, ...]   # values in field order, indexed by schema.index\n```\n\nField access becomes:\n```python\ndef get(self, field: str) -> AIFPLValue:\n    idx = self.schema.index.get(field)\n    if idx is None:\n        raise ...  # field not in schema\n    return self.slots[idx]\n```\n\nThat's a dict lookup for the index, then a tuple index \u2014 as fast as it gets in Python.\n\n`record-set` returns a new `AIFPLRecord` with the **same schema object** and a new slots tuple with one element replaced:\n```python\ndef set(self, field: str, value: AIFPLValue) -> 'AIFPLRecord':\n    idx = self.schema.index.get(field)\n    if idx is None:\n        raise ...  # schema violation\n    new_slots = self.slots[:idx] + (value,) + self.slots[idx+1:]\n    return AIFPLRecord(self.schema, new_slots)\n```\n\n---\n\n## The Uniqueness Optimisation Path\n\nThis is where the design pays off. When the VM is about to execute `record-set` and the refcount on the `AIFPLRecord` is 1 (unique), instead of building a new tuple it can:\n\n```python\n# Mutable fast path \u2014 only when unique\nslots_list = list(self.slots)\nslots_list[idx] = value\nobject.__setattr__(self, 'slots', tuple(slots_list))\nreturn self\n```\n\nThe schema is never touched \u2014 it's shared and immutable by nature. Only the slots tuple is replaced, and even then only one element changes. This is significantly cheaper than the general copy path, especially for large records.\n\n---\n\n## Comparison with Current AList\n\n| | `AIFPLAList` | `AIFPLRecord` |\n|---|---|---|\n| Backing store | `pairs` tuple + `_lookup` dict | `slots` tuple + shared `schema` |\n| Schema | Implicit, per-instance | Explicit, interned, shared |\n| Key lookup | Hash into `_lookup` | Hash into `schema.index` \u2192 tuple index |\n| Update cost | Rebuild pairs tuple + new `_lookup` | New slots tuple only (schema reused) |\n| Uniqueness opt | Copy whole pairs + rebuild dict | Replace one slot, reuse schema |\n| Higher-order ops | Yes (`dict-map` etc.) | No |\n| Add new key | Yes | No (schema violation) |\n\nThe record is strictly cheaper on every operation because the schema is separated out and shared.\n\n---\n\n## What Needs Touching in the Pipeline\n\nFollowing the AGENTS.md guide:\n\n1. **`aifpl_value.py`** \u2014 add `AIFPLRecordSchema` and `AIFPLRecord`\n2. **`aifpl_bytecode.py`** \u2014 add opcodes: `RECORD_MAKE`, `RECORD_GET`, `RECORD_SET`, `RECORD_HAS`, `RECORD_FIELDS`\n3. **`aifpl_vm.py`** \u2014 implement those opcodes\n4. **`aifpl_builtin_registry.py`** \u2014 register arities\n5. **`aifpl.py`** \u2014 add `record` variadic prelude constructor, schema interning\n6. **`aifpl_semantic_analyzer.py`** \u2014 teach it about `record?` type pattern\n7. **`aifpl_constant_folder.py`** \u2014 `record-has?` with a literal field name is constant-foldable\n8. **`aifpl_desugarer.py`** \u2014 if record construction gets special syntax\n9. **Tests** in `tests/aifpl/`\n\nThe constant-folding of `record-has?` is a nice bonus \u2014 since the schema is fixed, `(record-has? r \"name\")` where `\"name\"` is a literal can be folded to `#t` or `#f` at compile time if the schema is known.\n\n---\n\n## The One Open Question\n\n**Field ordering at construction** \u2014 does:\n```aifpl\n(record (\"age\" 30) (\"name\" \"Alice\"))\n```\nproduce a different schema from:\n```aifpl\n(record (\"name\" \"Alice\") (\"age\" 30))\n```\n\nFor schema interning to work efficiently, you probably want **canonical ordering** (alphabetical) so that field order at construction doesn't fragment the schema space. But that's a usability tradeoff \u2014 users might expect insertion order to be preserved for `record-fields`.\n\nThe pragmatic answer is probably: **sort fields alphabetically for schema identity, but preserve insertion order for `record-fields` output**. Or simply document that field order in construction is canonical and users should be consistent.\n\nWhat's your instinct on that?",
