      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Yes, though it's worth noting that Scheme and Lisp took quite different paths here, and none of them map perfectly onto what you're designing.\n\n---\n\n## Common Lisp \u2014 `defstruct` and CLOS\n\nCommon Lisp has two relevant mechanisms:\n\n**`defstruct`** is the closest precedent to your record concept:\n```lisp\n(defstruct person\n  name\n  age\n  role)\n\n(make-person :name \"Alice\" :age 30 :role \"admin\")\n(person-name my-person)        ; slot access\n(setf (person-age my-person) 31)  ; mutation (CL is not pure)\n```\n\nKey points:\n- Schema is **defined at compile time** as a named type\n- Generates typed accessor functions per field\n- Fixed fields, no dynamic addition\n- Supports inheritance between struct types\n\nThe schema-as-named-type approach is more explicit than what you're proposing (implicit interning), but the slot-based access idea is identical.\n\n**CLOS** (Common Lisp Object System) goes much further \u2014 full multiple inheritance, generic methods, method dispatch. Far more than you need.\n\n---\n\n## Scheme \u2014 `define-record-type` (SRFI-9, R7RS)\n\nThis is the most direct precedent:\n```scheme\n(define-record-type <person>\n  (make-person name age)\n  person?\n  (name person-name)\n  (age  person-age set-person-age!))\n```\n\nKey points:\n- **Named type** \u2014 `<person>` is a distinct type\n- **Named constructor** \u2014 `make-person` takes positional args\n- **Per-field accessors** \u2014 `person-name`, `person-age` are generated functions\n- **Optional mutators** \u2014 `set-person-age!` only if declared\n- `person?` is the type predicate\n\nThis is very explicit \u2014 you define the schema once, name it, and get typed accessors. The tradeoff is verbosity vs. clarity.\n\n---\n\n## Clojure \u2014 Records and Maps\n\nClojure is interesting because it's functional and has both:\n\n**`defrecord`** \u2014 named, typed, fixed-schema:\n```clojure\n(defrecord Person [name age role])\n(->Person \"Alice\" 30 \"admin\")\n(:name my-person)    ; keyword access\n(assoc my-person :age 31)  ; returns new Person, same type\n(assoc my-person :new-field \"x\")  ; returns plain map, not Person!\n```\n\nThat last point is fascinating \u2014 in Clojure, `assoc`-ing a new field onto a record **silently demotes it to a plain map**. Schema violation doesn't error, it just loses the type. That's probably not what you want.\n\n**Plain maps** are used for the dynamic case:\n```clojure\n{:name \"Alice\" :age 30}\n(:name my-map)\n(assoc my-map :role \"admin\")\n```\n\nClojure uses **keywords** (`:name`) rather than strings as keys \u2014 a distinct type that's self-describing and fast to compare. Relevant to your key-type question.\n\n---\n\n## Racket \u2014 Structs\n\nRacket's structs are closest to what you're describing implementation-wise:\n```racket\n(struct person (name age role)\n  #:transparent)   ; makes fields inspectable\n\n(person \"Alice\" 30 \"admin\")\n(person-name my-person)\n(struct-copy person my-person [age 31])  ; functional update\n```\n\n`struct-copy` is particularly elegant \u2014 it returns a new struct of the same type with specified fields updated, which maps directly onto your `record-set`. Racket also does the slot-index optimisation internally \u2014 field access is a direct vector reference, not a hash lookup.\n\n---\n\n## What the Precedents Suggest\n\nThe consistent theme across all of them is: **schemas are named and defined separately from instances**. None of them do implicit schema interning the way you'd be doing it.\n\nThe reason is probably that in those languages, the schema-as-named-type is load-bearing \u2014 it gives you:\n- A distinct type predicate (`person?` not just `record?`)\n- Generated typed accessors (`person-name` not just `record-get r \"name\"`)\n- A place to hang documentation, inheritance, etc.\n\nFor AIFPL specifically, named schemas are probably **too heavy** \u2014 you're an AI tool language, not a general-purpose application language. But the precedents do raise a question worth considering:\n\n**Do you want `record?` as a single predicate for all records, or per-schema predicates?**\n\nSomething like:\n```aifpl\n(record-instance? my-record person-schema)\n```\n\nThat's lightweight schema identity without full named types. It lets you write defensive code that checks not just \"is this a record\" but \"is this the right kind of record\" \u2014 which matters once you have multiple record shapes in play.\n\nRacket's approach feels like the closest match to your design goals \u2014 fixed schema, functional update via `struct-copy`, slot-based access, optional transparency. Worth looking at closely.",
