      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T11:01:54.487116+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Yes, exactly \u2014 and the Scheme/Racket precedent explains why.\n\n---\n\n## The Core Argument for Advance Definition\n\nWhen the schema is defined in advance, **the compiler knows the schema at every point where records of that type are used**. That means:\n\n- `record-get` with a literal field name can be compiled to a **direct slot index load** \u2014 no hash lookup at all, not even at runtime\n- `record-has?` with a literal field name folds to a constant at compile time\n- **Schema violations are compile-time errors**, not runtime errors \u2014 you catch `(record-set r \"typo\" v)` before it runs\n- The type predicate (`person?`) is a **cheap pointer comparison** against the schema object, not a structural check\n\nWith implicit interning, the compiler can't know the schema until construction time. You get O(1) runtime lookup, but you can't do better than that. With advance definition, you can get **zero-cost** field access \u2014 it's just an array index baked into the bytecode.\n\n---\n\n## What It Looks Like in AIFPL\n\nSomething like:\n\n```aifpl\n(define-record person (name age role))\n```\n\nThis is a **special form**, not a function call. It binds `person` as a schema value in the current scope, and implicitly defines:\n\n- `(person \"Alice\" 30 \"admin\")` \u2014 positional constructor\n- `(person? x)` \u2014 type predicate\n- `(person-name r)`, `(person-age r)`, `(person-role r)` \u2014 typed field accessors\n- `(person-set-age r 31)` \u2014 typed functional updaters\n\nThe accessors and updaters are **not hash lookups** \u2014 they're compiled to direct slot index operations because the compiler knows the schema at the call site.\n\n---\n\n## The Compiler's View\n\nWith advance definition, when the compiler sees:\n\n```aifpl\n(person-age my-record)\n```\n\nIt knows:\n- `person-age` is a generated accessor for schema `person`\n- `age` is slot index 1\n- Emit `LOAD_SLOT 1` \u2014 a single instruction, no lookup\n\nCompare to the implicit interning approach where `record-get` must be:\n1. Look up `\"age\"` in `schema.index` \u2014 hash lookup\n2. Use result to index `slots` \u2014 tuple index\n\nBoth are fast, but `LOAD_SLOT 1` is faster and **verifiable at compile time**.\n\n---\n\n## The Tradeoff\n\nThe cost is that `define-record` is a new **special form** \u2014 the most complex thing to add to the pipeline. It needs to be handled in:\n\n- The **semantic analyser** \u2014 to bind the schema and generated names in scope\n- The **IR builder** \u2014 to generate typed accessor/updater IR nodes\n- The **codegen** \u2014 to emit `LOAD_SLOT` / `STORE_SLOT` directly\n- The **desugarer** \u2014 possibly, if constructor syntax needs expansion\n\nWhereas implicit interning is just a new value type and some opcodes \u2014 much simpler to implement.\n\n---\n\n## Pragmatic Middle Ground\n\nYou could do it in two phases:\n\n**Phase 1** \u2014 implicit interning, runtime schema, `record-get`/`record-set` with hash lookup. Simpler to implement, gets the type into the language quickly.\n\n**Phase 2** \u2014 add `define-record`, generate typed accessors, teach the compiler to emit `LOAD_SLOT` for known schemas. The value type doesn't change \u2014 just the compiler gets smarter about known schemas.\n\nThe Phase 1 implementation doesn't block Phase 2. You're adding optimisation on top of a working foundation, which is the right order.\n\nDoes that phased approach feel right, or would you rather design for Phase 2 from the start even if it takes longer to get there?",
