    {
      "id": "55cd3998-2144-4cbd-9052-e1de128b8603",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T11:14:19.203776+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Agreed completely. Option A is the most honest design \u2014 everything is explicit, everything is a value, nothing happens by convention or arity magic.\n\n---\n\n## What Option A Actually Looks Like End-to-End\n\n```aifpl\n(let* ((person         (record-schema \"name\" \"age\" \"role\"))\n       (person?        (record-predicate person))\n       (person-name    (record-accessor person \"name\"))\n       (person-age     (record-accessor person \"age\"))\n       (person-role    (record-accessor person \"role\")))\n\n  (let ((alice (person \"Alice\" 30 \"admin\")))\n    (person? alice)           ; \u2192 #t\n    (person-name alice)       ; \u2192 \"Alice\"\n    (person-age alice)))      ; \u2192 30\n```\n\nEvery name is explicitly bound. Every value has a clear provenance. The compiler doesn't need to generate anything \u2014 `record-predicate` and `record-accessor` are just functions that return functions.\n\n---\n\n## Why This Is Actually Better Than Magic\n\nThe generated-name approach in Scheme has a subtle problem: the generated names (`person-name`, `person-age`) are **not first-class** in the way AIFPL values are. They're compiler artefacts. You can't pass `define-record-type` a computed list of field names, you can't conditionally define a schema, you can't build schemas from other schemas.\n\nIn Option A, `record-schema` is just a function. So:\n\n```aifpl\n; Schema from a computed list of fields - totally valid\n(let ((fields (list \"x\" \"y\" \"z\")))\n  (apply record-schema fields))\n```\n\nYou get the full power of the expression language applied to schema construction. That's something Scheme's `define-record-type` can never do.\n\n---\n\n## The Module Pattern\n\nIn a module, schemas and their accessors just become part of the exported alist:\n\n```aifpl\n(let* ((person      (record-schema \"name\" \"age\" \"role\"))\n       (person?     (record-predicate person))\n       (person-name (record-accessor person \"name\"))\n       (person-age  (record-accessor person \"age\")))\n\n  (alist\n    (list \"person\"      person)\n    (list \"person?\"     person?)\n    (list \"person-name\" person-name)\n    (list \"person-age\"  person-age)))\n```\n\nImporting code gets exactly what it needs, named exactly as the module author intended. No magic, no generated names leaking into unexpected scopes.\n\n---\n\n## The API Surface\n\nSo the complete record API becomes:\n\n| Value/Operation | What it is |\n|---|---|\n| `(record-schema f1 f2 ...)` | Returns a schema value |\n| `(person arg1 arg2 ...)` | Schema is callable as positional constructor |\n| `(record-predicate schema)` | Returns `(lambda (x) ...)` |\n| `(record-accessor schema field)` | Returns `(lambda (r) ...)` |\n| `(record-updater schema field)` | Returns `(lambda (r v) ...)` |\n| `(record-get r field)` | Generic field access by name |\n| `(record-set r field v)` | Generic functional update |\n| `(record-fields r)` | Returns list of field names |\n| `(record? x)` | Is x any record |\n| `(record-instance? x schema)` | Is x a record of this schema |\n| `(record=? r1 r2)` | Equality |\n| `(record!=? r1 r2)` | Inequality |\n\nThe distinction between `record-accessor`/`record-updater` (schema-bound, optimisable) and `record-get`/`record-set` (generic, string-keyed) is important \u2014 the former is what you use when you know the schema statically, the latter is for generic/reflective code.\n\n---\n\n## The Optimisation Story Is Clean Too\n\nBecause `record-accessor` takes the schema as an explicit argument, the constant folder can see:\n\n```aifpl\n(let ((person-age (record-accessor person \"age\")))\n  ...)\n```\n\nIf `person` is a known schema value and `\"age\"` is a literal, `person-age` is a function that will always load slot 1. The constant folder can replace it with a direct slot-index closure at compile time. No runtime hash lookup ever happens.\n\nThe explicitness that makes Option A feel elegant is also exactly what makes it optimisable. Those two things aren't in tension \u2014 they're the same property viewed from different angles.",
