    {
      "id": "b831a15f-fbc4-40d6-9c77-a58968be1824",
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T11:18:01.343783+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Yes, naturally \u2014 because a record field is just an `AIFPLValue`, and a record is an `AIFPLValue`, so nesting falls out for free.\n\n```aifpl\n(let* ((address      (record-schema \"street\" \"city\" \"country\"))\n       (person       (record-schema \"name\" \"age\" \"address\"))\n       (person-address (record-accessor person \"address\"))\n       (address-city   (record-accessor address \"city\")))\n\n  (let ((alice (person \"Alice\" 30 (address \"123 Main St\" \"Springfield\" \"US\"))))\n    (address-city (person-address alice))))   ; \u2192 \"Springfield\"\n```\n\nNo special support needed \u2014 the schemas are independent values, the accessors compose naturally, nesting is just function application.\n\n---\n\n## The Interesting Question Is Updates\n\nUpdating a nested field is where pure functional languages always feel the friction. To update Alice's city:\n\n```aifpl\n(let* ((person-address  (record-accessor person \"address\"))\n       (person-set-address (record-updater person \"address\"))\n       (address-set-city   (record-updater address \"city\")))\n\n  (let ((updated-alice\n          (person-set-address alice\n            (address-set-city (person-address alice) \"Shelbyville\"))))\n    updated-alice))\n```\n\nIt works, but it's inside-out \u2014 you read from the outside in, then write from the inside out. This is the classic functional update problem and it's not specific to your design. Haskell has lenses, Clojure has `update-in`, Elm has record update syntax.\n\n---\n\n## The `record-update-in` Question\n\nYou could offer a path-based updater as a convenience:\n\n```aifpl\n(record-update-in alice\n  (list person \"address\" address \"city\")\n  \"Shelbyville\")\n```\n\nBut this feels like it's pulling against the expression language grain \u2014 it requires runtime schema traversal rather than composed accessor calls. And it obscures what's actually happening.\n\nThe composed accessor approach, while verbose, is **transparent and optimisable**. Each step is a known slot access. A path-based approach is opaque at compile time.\n\n---\n\n## The Honest Answer\n\nNested records work perfectly for **reading**. For **writing**, the verbosity is real but it's an inherent property of immutable nested structures, not a flaw in this specific design. Every pure functional language faces it.\n\nThe question is whether the use cases you're anticipating involve a lot of deep nested updates. If they do, that's worth designing for explicitly. If reads dominate \u2014 which is typical for an AI tool language processing structured data \u2014 the current design is fine.\n\nWhat kind of access patterns are you expecting in practice?",
